Spatial memory in hearing and olfaction

Malina Szychowska

2023-06-16

Introduction

A key assumption in psychological science is that higher cognitive abilities interact similarly with any sensory input. For example, we can memorize song lyrics by either reading the text (visual) or listening to the song (auditory). The most well-understood cognitive domain is arguably the spatial memory and navigation system, featured in the 2014 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine. However, little is known about the roles of different senses in this system. Novel insights about differential sensory engagement in spatial memory would change our understanding of how the human mind is organized.

Smells and sounds may interact differently with spatial memory

Cognitive research is often based on visual tasks but results tend to be generalized to all the other senses. However, there are reasons to question this practice. Human olfaction (sense of smell) stands out from the other senses by having a direct and strong neuroanatomical connection to higher processing centers[1]. Olfaction operates through a network extending from the olfactory bulb that receives information from olfactory receptors in the nasal cavity, to the primary olfactory regions in the medial temporal lobe[1] - these are strongly connected with the core cognitive areas for memory and spatial navigation, the hippocampus (HC) and entorhinal cortex (EC)[2,3]. Indeed, the HC and EC uniquely engage in olfactory tasks (e.g., odor identification)[4,5], and primary olfactory areas strongly engage in smell-related cognitive tasks (e.g., odor-cued spatial navigation)[6]. I propose that these regions create a functionally integrated perceptual-cognitive system, an olfactory workspace, where representations of odors, spaces, and memories overlap. Developing evidence for such a framework is a theoretical aim of my project.

In contrast to olfaction, hearing shows a neuroanatomical separation of perceptual and cognitive processes, following the hierarchical organization typical for the neocortex, which makes it more similar to the visual system. Multiple nuclei in the auditory pathway are involved in different aspects of auditory processing, even before any sound information reaches the auditory primary cortex [see Figure 1 in 7]. Crucially, the auditory cortex is not directly connected with the HC[8,9], and the functional connectivity between these regions is weaker than that in olfaction[1,8]. The process of deriving spatial information from sounds is thus quite different from how such information is derived from smells.

Such different neuroanatomical and functional organization of the two senses might imply different engagement of olfaction and hearing in the mechanisms that underlie our spatial memory and navigation abilities, leading to distinct behavioral outcomes. The strong integration of olfaction and the HC-EC network could cause the spatial memory systems to prioritize smell-based memory, and therefore lead to retroactive interference, an overwriting of sound-based representations by smell-based representations. In line with this prediction, a recent study by colleagues from my collaborators showed olfactory dominance in an olfacto-visual categorization working memory (WM) task. Their results showed that incongruent smells impaired visual categorization more than incongruent pictures impaired olfactory categorization, revealing that smells can dominate our WM capacity[10]. In my studies, I will test whether similar olfactory dominance exists in our spatial memory. Specifically, I predict that Spatial memories for smells interfere with prior spatial memories for sounds more than vice versa, and are retained better in the long-term.

Methods

Participants

Equipment

For a long time, an obstacle in studying olfactory spatial memory in humans was the lack of equipment that would allow reliable deliverance of smells at variable locations in space. Typically, smells are presented with a large and heavy olfactometer that has pipes, glass jars filled with odorous liquids, motors, and fans. Such a setup requires participants to sit still during an experiment. Recently, our team overcame that limitation and developed a handheld olfactometer that is small, lightweight, easy to use, and compatible with a virtual reality (VR) setup (Figure 1a)[13]. Together with headphones and the VR system, it allowed participants to explore a virtual garden (Figure 1b) and interact with smells and sounds at multiple different locations - a novel and unique setup combining rigorous control over experimental variables with active navigation similar to real life.

Procedure

Participants task was to memoriz locations of smells and sounds within the VR arena (Figure 2a). All participants completed six stages of the experiment: (1) memory encoding in first condition, (2) memory recall in first condition, (3) memory encoding in second condition, (4) memory recall in second condition, (5) global recall with trials from both conditions presented in randomized order, (6) global recall again after one week (Figure 3). Whether a participant started with an auditory or olfactory condition was randomized.

In the encoding stages, participants explored the VR arena and memorized locations of gray spheres which gave off smells in the olfactory condition, and sounds in the auditory condition. The smell and sound objects were be associated with the same concepts (e.g., coffee)[24]. Gray spheres in olfactory and auditory conditions had distinct locations, therefore smell and sound objects associated with the same concept (e.g., coffee) were always be presented from spheres that had different locations.

In recall stages, participants were asked to place the objects that they have just encoded in their correct locations in an empty arena (smells in the olfactory condition, sounds in the auditory condition). In the global recall, smells and sounds were presented in a mixed sequence. Finally, participants were re-tested with global recall after a week to test which sensory spatial memory is better retained after a longer period of time, addressing the ongoing debate whether olfaction provides less differentiation than other senses between short- and long-term memory[25].

Performance was measured in terms of: distance error - a difference in virtual meters (vm) between the original and recalled location of the object; replacement time - time it took the participant to place the object; path tortuosity - ratio between the path length that the participant took and the shortest possible path; and sensory interference - normalized difference between the distance error to the original location and the interfered location (e.g., if the participant was asked to recall the location of the smell of coffee, original location would be the location of the coffee smell from the olfactory condition, and interfered location would be the location of the coffee brewer sound from the auditory condition).

Because of the proposed functional integration in the olfactory workspace and separation in the auditory system, the spatial memories of smells might have a priority over spatial memory of sounds. Thus, I expect that memories of smells will interfere with memory of sounds but the opposite will not be observed, and that memory of smells will be retained better than memory of sounds (H1). Specifically, location of sounds will be recalled less precisely (larger distance between recalled and original locations) and the recalled locations of sounds will gravitate towards locations of smells that represent the same concepts. This will establish a spatial olfactory dominance effect in spatial memory, similar to what was recently found in a non-spatial working memory task[10]. @ref(tab:genDescr)

Conceptual/semantic interference/confusion

Participants seem to perform similarly, regardless of the initial condition. Is there an effect of conceptual/semantic similarity on the location interference? Are people more likely to place the sphere wrongly in the location of an object that comes from different sensory modality but belongs to the same concept? (e.g., smell of coffee in place of the sound of a coffee maker).

Closeness score

One way to look at it, is to compare the distance error from the original location (recalled to original), with the distance to the interfered location (recalled to interfered; interfered being the same concept but different condition/sensory modality)

  summarise(mean_dis = mean(distance),

              filter(type == "hearing",
                     subtype == "spatial")
